4\fs20\cgrid {Section 6-1.  Definitions, Formation, and Membership\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {6\_1.1\tab Definitions\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-270\li990\widctlpar\tx-720\tx990\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\f4 a)\tab A Committee is a body of one or more persons, appointed by the Coordinating Committee (CC) or, in the case of the CC, elected by the General Assembly, to consider, investigate, or take action on certain internal party matters considered sensitive enough to warrant special supervision, as defined in its charge.\par b)\tab A Working Group is a body of one or more persons willing to participate, to consider, investigate, or take action on certain external party matters as defined in its charge.\par c)\tab The abbreviated term, Groups, is used within these Bylaws to refer to both Committees and Working Groups but not Subcommittees.\par d)\tab A Standing Group is any Group defined within these bylaws and whose charge deals with recurring business of the party.\par e)\tab An Ad Hoc (or Special) Group is created by the General Assembly to consider non-recurring business of the party or is otherwise expected to dissolve itself after completing its charge. Ad Hoc Groups may be established or dissolved by a 2/3 vote of the General Assembly.\par f)\tab A Subcommittee may be established or dissolved by a 2/3 vote of the relevant Group. All subcommittees are Ad Hoc and are expected to dissolve themselves after completing their charge.\par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {\par 6\_1.2\tab Standing Committee Membership\line Coordinating Committee (CC) membership is defined in Section 7-1.  Other Standing Committees shall be comprised of no more than seven members counting the CC Liaison (see paragraph 6-1.4). At least once a year or whenever vacancies exist, the active counties, group coordinators, and individual CC members shall be given the opportunity to submit nominations or recommendations for Standing Committee membership. Eligible candidates must have attended at least two prior State Plenaries within the previous 12 months and demonstrate a working knowledge of the State Party Bylaws and operating procedures. Standing Committee members shall be appointed by the Coordinating Committee subject to confirmation by the General Assembly. Members shall serve for two years in staggered terms whenever possible. Any Standing Committee member can be recalled with an 80% vote of the CC.\par \par 6\_1.3\tab Ad Hoc Committee Membership\line Ad Hoc Committee members shall be elected by the General Assembly. Subcommittee members shall be appointed by the Group which creates the subcommittee. Committee members shall serve for two years or until the committee is dissolved, whichever comes first. Any committee member can be recalled with an 80% vote of the body which appointed or elected the member.\par \par 6\_1.4\tab Working Group Membership\line Working Group membership shall be open to any Green Party member willing to participate. The expression of non stand aside concerns and voting privileges are reserved for those members who have attended or participated in at least one previous Working Group meeting within the previous 12 months.\par \par 6\_1.5\tab Group Liaison to the Coordinating Committee\line Each Group shall be assigned a Coordinating Committee (CC) member by the CC to serve as Liaison to the CC, an ex-officio voting member of the Group. The Liaison is charged with facilitating communications between the Group and the CC. Liaisons appointed to Standing Committees also serve as the Committee's Coordinator (see Coordinator duties, paragraph 6-2.5).\par \par 6-1.6\tab Group Coordinators\line In addition to any CC appointed Liaison/Coordinators, the Group }{\b shall}{ elect a Co-Coordinator and }{\b may}{ elect additional Co-Coordinators from among its membership subject to confirmation by the General Assembly (see Coordinator duties, paragraph 6-2.5). Elected Coordinators shall serve for two years in staggered terms or until a successor is appointed or elected.\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {\page Section 6-2.  General Duties, Authority, and Functions.\par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {\par 6\_2.1\tab Work Plan\line Each Group shall prepare a yearly work plan to be submitted along with any budget requests. The work plan will identify what are the objectives of the Group for that year and what, if any, proposals it would want to bring before the General Assembly and a projected timeline for the Group\rquote s activities. The stated objectives must be congruent with the Group\rquote s Statement of Purpose and the Goals and Strategies of the GPCA.\par \par 6\_2.2\tab Meetings and Deliberations\line Each Group shall determine for itself how many meetings are necessary to achieve the objectives outlined in its work plan. Each Group shall prepare and make public the proposed meeting agenda at least two weeks in advance of the meeting date. Any last minute agenda changes shall be for information items only and not for action. All deliberative and decision-making meetings shall be open to all Green Party members unless closed by a 2/3 vote of the membership. However, even closed meetings may be required by the General Assembly to publish the minutes of its proceedings. \par \par 6\_2.3\tab Proposal Authority\line All proposals to be considered by the General Assembly must first be approved and presented by a Standing Committee or Standing Working Group. Exceptions may be allowed for proposals to be considered in the Consent Calendar (Paragraph 5\_9.11).\par \par 6\_2.4\tab Proposal Presentation\line Groups will act in the role of advocate for the proposals they present to the General Assembly. The presenter will disclose to the General Assembly whether the Group brings the proposal forward with consensus or by a vote. If by a vote, the details of the vote will be presented.\par \par 6\_2.5\tab Coordinator Duties\line The responsibilities of the Group Coordinators shall include:\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-270\li990\widctlpar\tx-720\tx990\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\f4 a)\tab Establishing the agenda of the Group;\par b)\tab Facilitating and coordinating the activities of the Group;\par c)\tab Presenting Group proposals or other official communications to the General Assembly;\par d)\tab Maintaining a physical notebook containing the Group\rquote s Statement of Purpose, membership information, meeting minutes, and any other documents relevant to the work of the Group;\par e)\tab Filing meeting agendas and minutes with the Coordinating Committee Secretary in a timely fashion including a summary report after the conclusion of a General Assembly meeting with general contact information, active membership list, and status report;\par f)\tab Designating a temporary Acting Coordinator to perform the duties outlined above whenever they are unable to perform them and notifying the CC and the Group membership.\par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {\par \par }\pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx-720\tx360\adjustright \caps\f21\fs20\cgrid {\page Article 7.  Standing Committees of the General Assembly\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 7-1.  Coordinating Committee (AKA the CC)\par }\pard\plain \fi720\li720\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard \li360\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs20 [no change] \par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 7-2  Finance Committee (formerly Section 7-10)\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-2.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The Finance Committee is charged with overseeing the financial operations of the GPCA. This includes working with the Treasurer to:\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-270\li990\widctlpar\tx-720\tx990\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\f4 a)\tab Collect county dues to the GPCA and any other moneys allocated to the GPCA;\par b)\tab Facilitate the allocation and disbursement of funds;\par c)\tab Provide quarterly financial reports to the CC;\par d)\tab Provide an annual budget report to the plenary;\par e)\tab Provide any official reporting required by the State of California;\par f)\tab Be the conduit for GPCA fundraising activities.\par }\pard\plain \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard \li360\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs20 [the rest of the original Section 7-10 is not changed]\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 7-3.  Bylaws Committee\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-3.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The Bylaws Committee is charged with maintaining the GPCA Bylaws and assisting with their amendment or revision. All Bylaw amendment proposals must be reviewed by the Bylaws Committee before submission to the General Assembly.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-3.2\tab Bylaws Interpretation\line In cases of bylaw ambiguity or procedural disagreement, the General Assembly shall decide for itself the meaning of its bylaws or the appropriate procedure to be followed. In between General Assembly meetings, the Coordinating Committee shall decide these questions subject to review at the next General Assembly meeting. The Bylaws Committee and its coordinators are charged with assisting with the interpretation of the Bylaws and the resolution of procedural questions.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 7-4.  Platform Committee\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-4.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The Platform Committee is charged with maintaining the Platform of the GPCA and assisting with it\rquote s amendment or revision. All platform proposals must be reviewed by the Platform Committee before submission to the General Assembly.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-4.2\tab Platform Research and Interpretation\line The Platform Committee shall endeavor to identify issues not in the platform and to suggest and formulate platform planks with substantial input from appropriate experts in the field. The Platform Committee shall also assist the General Assembly, the Coordinating Committee, and the Media Spokespersons with formulating positions or statements on issues or initiatives related to official platform positions.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 7-5.  International Protocol Committee\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-5.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The International Protocol Committee is charged with administrating, hosting, and networking with international Greens.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {\page Section 7-6.  Clearinghouse Committee\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-6.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The Clearinghouse Committee is charged with maintaining an archive of all GPCA documents and data. The Clearinghouse Committee is also charged with facilitating internal and external communications and information dissemination including maintaining the GPCA website and returning communications received by phone, email, and postal mail.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {7-6.2\tab Ex Officio Members\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-270\li990\widctlpar\tx-720\tx990\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\f4 a)\tab The Liaison to the Secretary of State.\par b)\tab A webmaster appointed by the committee.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\tx-720\tx360\adjustright \caps\f21\fs20\cgrid {ARTICLE 8.  STANDING WORKING GROUPS OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY \par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 8-1.  Organizing and Outreach Working Group\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {8-1.1\tab Duties and Authority\line The Organizing & Outreach Working Group is charged with facilitating voter registration activities and organizing locals by:\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-270\li990\widctlpar\tx-720\tx990\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\f4 a)\tab Coordinating locals into statewide efforts to register Green Party voters and do public outreach through tabling;\par b)\tab Providing training for county locals in tabling;\par c)\tab Developing, maintaining, and providing resources for tabling efforts and organization of locals;\par d)\tab Maintaining lists of registered Green Party voters;\par e)\tab Publishing a statewide GPCA newsletter;\par f)\tab Engaging in direct mailings statewide to Green Party membership for purposes of fundraising and membership outreach.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 8-2.  Campaigns and Candidates Working Group\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {8-2.1\tab Duties\line To educate Green Party members about our electoral strategy with an emphasis on local initiatives that open up the system and local candidates who can win; to identify key political campaigns in which Green Party activists can play a pivotal role; to educate Greens about the importance of running credible candidates in strategically chosen races and avoiding poor candidates and nonconstructive races; where appropriate, to identify registered Greens who would make credible candidates; to promote regional strategies for winning campaigns so that Greens avoid spreading resources too thinly; to train Green Party activists in methods of waging political campaigns either for candidates or for issues; and to raise money for Green Party campaigns.\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 8-3.  Electoral Reform Working Group\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {8-3.1\tab Duties\line To educate Green Party members, the public and the media about electoral reforms that will open up the political system, including Proportional Representation, Instant Runoff Voting, and public financing of elections; to identify strategies for enacting these reforms such as promoting the use of Proportional Representation for County Council elections; to encourage Greens to initiate or support successful local campaigns for electoral reform; and to advise GPCA of internal party voting mechanisms and electoral policy\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \caps\f4\fs20\cgrid {Section 8-4.  Green Issues Working Group\par }\pard\plain \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\adjustright \f4\cgrid {\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\fi-720\li720\widctlpar\tx-720\tx720\adjustright \f4\fs20\cgrid {8-4.1\tab Duties\line To identify current issues and events for which the GPCA or its platform has no position; to sponsor debate of issues that may impact the platform; to sponsor resolutions on current issues to be passed by the GPCA plenary body; when appropriate, to interface with the Platform Standing Committee and with candidates whom are running for office as Green Party members; and where appropriate, to build coalitions with other organizations.\par }}